c&index=21>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   re: trauma</span><hr size=1> &quot;Do you know about the severe mental trauma that can come with having an abortion?&quot;<br>
<br>
I know that abortion does not equal mental trauma, but I don't think anyone here has suggested that there is NO trauma at all. Let's say we concede it is at least psycholgically stressful to have an abortion. The question at hand is whether it is not less so than being forced to carry a child. <br>
<br>
Oh--and in rape cases the trauma would certainly be greater, but for those that find abortion to be murder or claim the fetus us a life who's right to be born supercedes the mother's right to abort, making these incest/rape exceptions in incongruous. At least be consistent.<br>
<br>
&quot;Even in the situation where a person is raped, a mother who has an abortion rarely walks away from the process as mentally healthy as before the proceedure.&quot;<br>
<br>
Noone who has been raped walks away as mentally healthy. Would the woman be more healthy if she were forced to carry the rapist's child? <br>
<br>
&quot;This is because the body has already begun releasing certain chemicals that create the strong maternal bond.&quot;<br>
<br>
These are not strong enough to create the kind of bond you insinuate. I know this from personal experience. In fact, most women don't find pregnancy and motherhood &quot;real&quot; or hitting home in a visceral way until the 2nd tri-mester when they start showing and having more physical signs and the risk of miscarriage is much lower. I'm not saying you don't feel anything at all for a clump of cells in your uterus, but there is a definite difference in emotion when the baby is wanted and after it's been a few months and you can &quot;feel&quot; him/her.<br>
<br>
&quot;As far as adoption,(which I encourage over abortion in non-rape related cases)&quot;<br>
Why? Do the babies of rape have less right to life? Again--I am pro-choice, but am always astounded by those who make the case that a fertilized egg is life, then make an exception based on donors. The source of the sperm is morally irrelevant if you argue from the position that the fertilized egg is life and that life supercedes the rights of the mother. (maybe you are not really a pro-lifer after all, but it seems this way--please correct me if I'm wrong).<br>
<br>
&quot;In most cases that bond is too strong, resulting in a mother who is not well equipped to raise a child, but who will raise it because they believe that it is not a sign of love to give the child to someone who is better suited to the job of mother.&quot;<br>
<br>
What?!!? What makes you think women who choose to raise their own children believe adoption is not a sign of love? <br>
<br>
&quot;It is just my opinion, but I believe that rape victims suffer enough mental trauma from the incident that they should not need to face these additional traumas.&quot;<br>
<br>
We agree rape victims should not have to suffer additional trauma. What we seem to disagree on is whether terminating a resulting preganancy is more traumatic than being forced to carry the child to term and give birth then either raise the baby (a result of rape/incest) or give it up for adoption. Do you honestly purport the latter is psychologically easier? <br>
<br>
Though it is admittedley not relevant in terms of debate, may I ask if you have ever been raped or had an abortion or given a child up for adoption? You speak easily about the emotions involved as if you have 1st hand knowledge and it differs so very, very much from my own first hand knowledge of such things.<br>
<br>
ST <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=doublelatte>Double Latte</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Got Milk?</span><br>  Posts: 183<br> <font color=#3333ff>(6/12/03 1:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=213.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Hospitals</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Do you know about the severe mental trauma that can come with having an abortion?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Phoenix, are you new here? I probably know far better than most people the emotional issues surrounding of abortion. I had a late-term abortion of a very loved and very much wanted baby, due to lethal defects that meant his life would have been very short and and filled with suffering. Since that time I have been active in pro-choice politics and met hundreds of women (both IRL and online) who've experience abortion for any number of reasons. I've yet to meet even one who did so for stupid or selfish reasons.<br>
<br>
I tried to make it clear in my post that I thought the morning after pill less traumatic than early-term abortion; early-term abortion less traumatic than late term; almost any abortion less traumatic than giving away a live baby child and spending the rest of your life wondering about it - or watching a dying baby suffer needlessly. At 20 weeks, the maternal bond I felt for my gently kicking baby went FAR deeper than mere &quot;chemicals.&quot; <br>
<br>
I am thoroughly pro-choice. I don't think any woman should ever be forced to carry any pregnancy, regardless of circumstance. I love babies, and think they deserve quality parenting and quality of life in all cases. Only mothers can make the best decisions about their own pregnancies. Or as the bumper sticker goes &quot;If you can't trust me with a choice, how can you trust me with a child?&quot;<br>
<br>
My heart goes out to rape victims and I would hope their medical care providers would fully support them rather than reduce their choices in ANY way. I was only pointing out that your scenario of &quot;no access to morning after pill = bad parenting creates more rapists&quot; had a flaw.<br>
<br>
DL<br>
