<br>
First of all, that little scenario was just a hypothetical situation, as I pointed out.  I never said that all cases end up this way, I'm just saying that they could.<br>
<br>
Second, I believe in the morning-after pill for rape victims.  However, I have met many people who wanted to abort a child because they chose to have unprotected sex, while not wanting the consequences of having a child.  I believe that if you are willing to commit a deed, then you should also be willing to live with the consequences.  That is why I make the exception for rape victims, they did not choose to be raped, they were stripped of any choice in the matter.  I also make the exception because the state of the mother greatly affects the state of the child.  Being pregnant is stressful enough, but being raped and pregnant is enough stress to cause the release of sufficient amounts of chemicals that, if not immediately harming the child, will likely cause long term damage to the unborn child.  <br>
<br>
Third, my &quot;It is just my opinion, but I believe that rape victims suffer enough mental trauma from the incident that they should not need to face these additional traumas.&quot; comment was to indicate that I think that it is much better to allow the mother to have access to the morning-after pill than to force them to undergo one of the other options.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Though it is admittedley not relevant in terms of debate, may I ask if you have ever been raped or had an abortion or given a child up for adoption? You speak easily about the emotions involved as if you have 1st hand knowledge and it differs so very, very much from my own first hand knowledge of such things.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well, let me put it this way, I am a male med student.  I work with the people who have to make these decisions all the time.  I am also very empathetic to others.  So although I don't have first hand experience with making the choice, I have been exposed to the situation enough to have a good understanding of many of the possible outcomes.<br>
<br>
Finally, DBC, it confuses me that the begining of your post inferrs that you are not in agreement with me, but the rest of your post seems to make the same arguments that I have made.  The primary role of any medical institution is to promote the health and well being of its patrons, and not to limit their care in any way.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=powertotherae>Powertotherae</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Satan's Lil' Minion</span><br>  Posts: 279<br> <font color=#3333ff>(6/12/03 4:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=213.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: re: trauma</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Being pregnant is stressful enough, but being raped and pregnant is enough stress to cause the release of sufficient amounts of chemicals that, if not immediately harming the child, will likely cause long term damage to the unborn child.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
