I do not impose my beliefs upon others.  I find that to be a rude and unacceptable thing to do.  I realize that the circumstances are always different, and that because of that, no rule set in stone will work for all situations.  When I graduate, and am a fully licensed doctor, my job will be to ensure that my patients make an educated decision as to the care provided.  I personally don't enjoy the thought of abortions, but if that is the course of action that the patient decides upon, then that is the type of care that I will provide.  If a patient came to me because they had just been raped and thought that conception was a possibility, I would tell them about each option available.(Abortion/Adoption/morning-after pill/Child care.)  I would then inform them as to what the side-effects(both common and rare side effects) are of each option, and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>if</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> they wanted, I would help them in choosing a course of action.  But I always leave the final decision in their hands, and respect that decision.<br>
<br>
Leah,<br>
I will not say that I can experience what it feels like, but I should tell you that one of the people who did my med-school interview would disagree with you.  One of the questions that she asked was this.<br>
&quot;You are a 16 year old girl, who has just been informed by your doctor that you are pregnant.  You are sexually active, and thus do not know who the father is.  Your parents do not know about your sexual life at all.  How do you feel?&quot;<br>
She had been in this situation herself, and thus had first hand experience with the emotions that would be present.  Rather than to simply list off the emotions that were to be expected, I essentially became that person.  My response could easily show the intensity of certain emotions, and how some of the emotions were less powerful.  After the interview that interviewer came up to me and said that she was surprised by my answer.  She had never gotten a response that was that intense and exact before.  So she would probably say that despite the fact that I am &quot;still a man&quot;, I understand very well the impact of the situation.  That is why my last post said that I was very empathetic. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dbc67>DBC67</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Avatar of Reason</span><br>  Posts: 274<br> <font color=#3333ff>(6/12/03 6:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=213.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.rune-stone.net/Pitt/avatar.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: re: trauma</span><hr size=1> I don't know if I mentioned this before, I think I may have...but I swallowed a live frog once.  It squirmed around in my belly for what seemed like hours (actually prolly about 10-20 minutes in reality.)  <br>
